---
import Article from "../../../layouts/Article.astro";
import KeyTakeaway from "../../../components/KeyTakeaway.astro";
import InfoBox from "../../../components/InfoBox.astro";
---

<Article
  title="Best Beginner Corporations in Terraforming Mars"
  description="Which corporations to pick when you're learning the game — and which to avoid."
  game="terraforming-mars"
  gameTitle="Terraforming Mars"
  category="Strategy"
  publishDate="2025-05-06"
>
  <p>
    Your corporation defines your starting resources, income, and strategy for the
    entire game. Some corporations are intuitive. Others require deep card knowledge
    to use well. Here's what to pick when you're starting out.
  </p>

  <KeyTakeaway answer="Start with Beginner Corporation (the rules suggest it for a reason), then graduate to Helion, Ecoline, or Thorgate. Avoid Inventrix and Phobolog until you know the card deck." />

  <h2>Best Corporations for New Players</h2>

  <div class="my-8 space-y-6">
    <div class="p-6 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-bark/10 relative overflow-hidden">
      <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 px-4 py-1.5 bg-emerald-500 text-white text-xs font-bold rounded-bl-xl">START HERE</div>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <span class="text-3xl">🏭</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-heading font-bold text-xl text-bark">Beginner Corporation</h3>
          <span class="text-xs text-bark/40">42 M€ + 10 free project cards</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-bark/60">
        The rulebook recommends this for your first game — and it's right. You get 10 free project cards
        (normally you'd pay 3 M€ each to keep them), which means more options without having to make
        painful discard decisions. No special ability to track.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="p-6 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-bark/10 relative overflow-hidden">
      <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 px-4 py-1.5 bg-blue-500 text-white text-xs font-bold rounded-bl-xl">GREAT 2ND GAME</div>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <span class="text-3xl">☀️</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-heading font-bold text-xl text-bark">Helion</h3>
          <span class="text-xs text-bark/40">42 M€ · 3 Heat production</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-3">
        <span class="px-2 py-0.5 bg-orange-50 text-orange-700 text-[11px] font-semibold rounded-full">Heat = Money</span>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-bark/60">
        Can spend heat as M€. This is incredibly forgiving — you always have extra resources.
        The 3 heat production also lets you raise temperature without spending cards, giving
        you TR income for free. Hard to play badly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="p-6 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-bark/10 relative overflow-hidden">
      <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 px-4 py-1.5 bg-blue-500 text-white text-xs font-bold rounded-bl-xl">GREAT 2ND GAME</div>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <span class="text-3xl">🌿</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-heading font-bold text-xl text-bark">Ecoline</h3>
          <span class="text-xs text-bark/40">36 M€ · 2 Plant production · +1 starting plant</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-3">
        <span class="px-2 py-0.5 bg-emerald-50 text-emerald-700 text-[11px] font-semibold rounded-full">Cheap Greenery</span>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-bark/60">
        Greenery tiles cost 7 plants instead of 8. Combined with starting plant production,
        you'll be placing greeneries faster than anyone. Simple, visual strategy: make plants,
        place tiles, raise oxygen, score VPs.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="p-6 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-bark/10">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
        <span class="text-3xl">⚡</span>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-heading font-bold text-xl text-bark">Thorgate</h3>
          <span class="text-xs text-bark/40">48 M€ · 1 Energy production</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-3">
        <span class="px-2 py-0.5 bg-yellow-50 text-yellow-700 text-[11px] font-semibold rounded-full">Cheap Power Cards</span>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-bark/60">
        Power-tagged cards cost 3 M€ less. Energy production cards are common in the deck,
        so this discount triggers frequently. Good for learning how energy and heat interact.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Corporations to Avoid Early On</h2>

  <div class="my-6 space-y-3">
    <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
      <span class="text-lg shrink-0">⚠️</span>
      <div>
        <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-red-800">Inventrix</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-red-700/70 mt-1">Lets you ignore global requirements. Powerful in expert hands but confusing for beginners who don't yet know which cards have requirements worth bypassing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
      <span class="text-lg shrink-0">⚠️</span>
      <div>
        <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-sm text-red-800">Phobolog</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-red-700/70 mt-1">Titanium is worth 4 M€ instead of 3. Great if you know which space-tagged cards are in the deck. Underwhelming if you don't draw space cards.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <InfoBox type="tip" title="The Real Tip">
    In your first 2–3 games, don't stress about corporations. Focus on understanding the three global parameters (temperature, oxygen, oceans), how production works, and which cards generate VP. Corporation mastery comes later.
  </InfoBox>
</Article>
